<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-25-0167 </DOCNO><TEXT>Discusses the history of coal use in the United States since World WarI and highlights the main factors likely to influence its future. Oneof these is the price differential between oil and coal, which is affectedby issues which affect the cost of producing coal. Political issues,such as the decline in the mining labour force and conflict between easternand western coal industries will also influence coal's future. Acid rainis discussed in terms of the conflicting policy approaches to it, forexample, action now versus more research and development. The paper concludesthat on balance coal can be considered the major fuel source for theUS economy, but stress is laid on the importance of scientists, engineersand lawmakers getting on with efforts to burn it cleanly and turn itinto economically affordable gas and liquid forms.</TEXT></DOC>